Here is a simplified, beginner-friendly split of the **42 Webserv** project adapted for **HTTP/1.0** (instead of the usual HTTP/1.1 requirement in most campuses).

HTTP/1.0 (RFC 1945) is noticeably simpler than 1.1 because:

- No persistent connections by default → server **closes** the TCP connection after each response (no need to handle "Connection: keep-alive")
- No mandatory `Host` header (but still good to parse it if present)
- No chunked transfer encoding
- Much simpler connection management → one request = one connection = one response → close

This makes the project significantly easier for beginners with zero HTTP/socket knowledge — ideal for getting something working quickly.

### Quick prerequisites (do together — 1–2 days)
- Read **RFC 1945** (HTTP/1.0) — focus only on:
  - Section 4 (Message Types)
  - Section 5 (Request)
  - Section 6 (Response)
  - Section 8 (only common headers: Content-Type, Content-Length, Date, Server, Allow)
  - Skip authentication, caching, negotiation, etc.
- Watch short videos:
  - "What is HTTP?" (5–10 min)
  - "TCP sockets in C/C++ basics" (Beej's guide style, ~20 min)
- Create a shared git repo + agree on:
  - C++98 only
  - One Makefile
  - Simple config (e.g. `webserv.conf` with port + root only at first)

### 3-Person split (zero previous knowledge friendly)

**Person A – "Sockets & Connections"**
Focus: Everything low-level + connection lifecycle (the foundation)

Tasks:
- Learn `socket()`, `bind()`, `listen()`, `accept()`, `read()`, `write()`, `close()`
- Make server listen on a port (start with hardcoded 8080)
- Use **select()** or **poll()** to handle multiple connections
- Accept new clients → create a simple Client struct/class (fd, buffer, state)
- Read raw data from clients until you see `\r\n\r\n` (end of headers) or connection closes
- Detect client disconnect (read returns 0) → close socket
- After sending response → **always close** the client socket (HTTP/1.0 style)
- Handle timeouts if possible (simple: close after ~30s inactivity)

First milestone (week 1 goal):
- Server starts, `telnet localhost 8080` connects
- You type `GET / HTTP/1.0` + two enters → server reads it, doesn't crash
- Handles 5–10 simultaneous telnet connections

**Person B – "Request Understanding"**
Focus: Parsing the incoming HTTP/1.0 request + very basic config

Tasks:
- Read RFC 1945 section 5 → understand request format
- Write parser for request-line: `METHOD SP REQUEST-URI SP HTTP-Version CRLF`
  - Only support `GET` and maybe `HEAD` at first
  - Check version is exactly `HTTP/1.0` (400 Bad Request otherwise)
- Parse headers (until double CRLF):
  - Store in map<string, string> or vector<pair<string,string>>
  - Important ones: `Content-Length` (for future POST), `User-Agent`, `Date` (ignore most)
- Parse URI:
  - Split path vs ?query (query can be ignored at first)
  - Decode %XX if you want bonus points later
- Very simple config parser (start minimal):
  - port
  - root directory
  - index file(s) (e.g. index.html)
  - Later: one location block with allowed methods

First milestone:
- Takes raw string from Person A → gives structured data:
  - method, path, version
  - map of headers
  - "is valid?" flag (or error code)

**Person C – "Response Builder & File Serving"**
Focus: Creating correct HTTP/1.0 responses + serving content

Tasks:
- Read RFC 1945 section 6 → understand response format
- Build Response class/struct:
  - Status line: `HTTP/1.0 200 OK` or `404 Not Found`, etc.
  - Mandatory-ish headers:
    - `Date` (current time in GMT)
    - `Server` ("Webserv/1.0" or similar)
    - `Content-Type` (guess from extension: .html → text/html, .jpg → image/jpeg, etc.)
    - `Content-Length` (file size in bytes)
  - Body: file content or error message
- Serve static GET requests:
  - Combine config root + request path
  - If directory → look for index file
  - If file → read & send
  - If not found → 404 with simple HTML error page
- HEAD → same headers as GET but no body
- Simple error responses (400, 403, 404, 500)

First milestone:
- Given method/path → returns full response string (status + headers + body)
- Can serve one `index.html` file correctly

### Suggested order & timeline (~3–5 weeks for minimal working version)

**Week 1** (foundation)
- Everyone: basics of HTTP/1.0 + sockets
- A: listening + accept + raw read loop with select()
- B: dummy request parser (just method + path + version)
- C: function that returns hardcoded "HTTP/1.0 200 OK\r\nContent-Type: text/plain\r\n\r\nHello from 42!"

**Week 2** (first real request-response)
- Integrate: A reads → B parses → C builds response → A sends + closes connection
- Add simple config (port + root)

**Week 3** (realistic static site)
- Serve real files (html, css, images)
- Add 404 + directory → index.html logic
- Basic error pages

**Week 4+** (polish & extras — if time)
- POST support (save uploaded file — Person B + C collaborate)
- Allowed methods per location (405 Method Not Allowed)
- Autoindex (directory listing) as bonus
- More status codes (403, 500…)
- Test with real browser + curl -0 (forces HTTP/1.0)

### HTTP/1.0 advantages for beginners
- Much easier multiplexing (no keep-alive logic)
- No need to parse "Connection:" header for persistence
- No chunked encoding nightmare
- Easier to test manually with telnet

Start small → get `GET /` serving one file in browser using HTTP/1.0 → then expand.